 exerted for higher growth (choosing 5% best individuals), we would be indirectly selecting for abalones with lower food intake (correlated responses of -11 to -15%); or lower metabolic demands of (-14 to -24%), if the selection was applied to young or near-harvest adults, respectively. In turn, shell length could be enhanced up to 18% per generation. These results suggest that higher growth in red abalone is genetically associated with a more efficient use of food and a lower metabolic demand. The possibility to reduce food intake or metabolic demands by selecting for faster growing abalones would be a very positive development for the sustainability of this culture.
